Text.Value: *Her mind cools - acceptance is coloured by disappointment.*
It's only fair that they should earn their keep.
Good. When I am stronger, we are stronger.
You absorbed a tadpole's essence to accomplish this change. Do you have more?
I do not need to like myself - and you need not like me either - for us to exact vengeance on those who infected us.
But whatever life remains to us, I would gladly spend it fighting at your side. And lying with you at night.
This bond we share... I believe it is alurlssrin. If that is so, it will last as long as we do.
I did not think we would ever share anything more than an uneasy alliance, born of our mutual enmity for the Absolute.
I have somebody else already.
I do not need to - I want to. You fascinate me.
All I ask is that you do not waste them.
In spite of the danger, I was happy. I knew myself, and I understood the world around me.
I did not expect to meet one still sworn to Lolth who would understand me.
*A flicker of warmth had spread from her mind to yours - it is snuffed out in an instant.*
Think this, feel that, hate them.
No. You need to figure this out for yourself.
A survivor.
We need to set some rules about tadpole usage.
When we first met - before Moonrise - I intruded on your thoughts without hesitation, and took what I needed from your memories.
But I would like to touch your thoughts again, now that my mind is my own. May I?
It's mine - I'll do as I wish with it.
Paper spun from spider-silk, Everdark ink drawn from dragon scales, and nefarious lies dreamt in darkness.
I do not disagree. But to turn them away would be wasteful.
I'd prefer to just tell you.
Yes. And if they work hard enough for long enough, the city might allow them to earn their freedom one day.
We need one another as allies, but I want more from you than that. I want all of you.
They'd be better off seeking help elsewhere if all they can hope for here is to die for Baldur's Gate.
Before the Absolute, I lived a life of certainties. I knew that I was destined for greatness because I was born to it.
A monster.
Are you suggesting they be used as slaves?
Stop this. I'm not your mirror.
Let me see.
If they are weak, they will die, whether it is on the road or in the defence of the city. And if they are strong, they will find a way to survive.
You are trying to raise my spirits. I appreciate it, but any joy the sight of Orin's corpse brings me is but a speck of comforting shade.
That's what I want. I'll let them know.
Wait. Let me speak.
I do not think anyone can be the mirror to their own soul, and even if I could, it is your view of me that I want to see.
If I must be a greater monster than the Absolute to survive it, then I shall be. Perhaps one day, if you survive too, you will realise that I had no choice.
But we can talk of this later. For now, let us be glad that we still draw breath. And that Orin does not.
Of course. I do not hide anything from you.
I agree. They should offer them shelter from the danger that is coming.
When the Absolute fell silent, I thought I would be alone. I expected to spend my days among surface-dwellers who knew nothing of my culture.
Sorry. Old habits.
Correct. I am glad that you see things as I do - no matter what victory we have won, we cannot afford to relax our guard.
Open your mind - let her in.
Truly, the citizens of Baldur's Gate are a model of shrewd wisdom that we should all hope to emulate.
Ink and paper are not as insidious as the voice of the Absolute, but they send out their commands all the same.
Push into her mind.
Even honest words can obscure meaning. Thought and feeling are pure, without artifice.
Indeed. They could be a convenient source of food if the city falls under siege.
That is enough.
And they would know that they could depend on me. Feared, venerated, adored. I would be everything to them.
Perhaps you think it would be better for them to starve or be slaughtered here, while the citizens hide behind their walls?
I'm flattered.
Not right now.
Show me myself through your eyes - let me see what I am to you.
Now, nothing is certain.
Few people could face a Chosen of Bhaal. You did.
As you wish.
They're not the city's responsibility - the patriars have right to turn away anyone they wish.
*Her mind touches yours, feather-light and hesitant. A stark contrast to the confidence with which her thoughts intruded on yours in the past.*
No. Respect my privacy.
I did not ask permission.
Only until it is done?
If you will not use it, give it to me.
A feeling.
I want you too.
*Those doubts cluster in swarms, and the thickest is around her sense of self. She pushes past, revealing the image of her you hold in your mind.*
I agree.
I would use the Mouth to ensure the people did not trust one another. Suspicion creates doubt, and doubt creates dependency.
Perhaps longer, if you wish it.
Free of the Absolute's influence, the tadpole is a boon. It has expanded my mind, and improved my body.
I trust you.
I felt you, peering into my mind. What are you hoping to find?
Then I have misunderstood you, and myself.
Until my time in the cult of the Absolute, I had spent little time on the surface, except to raid and pillage.
What we share is no more than ssinssrigg, a passion that burns fierce, but has no foundation.
Indeed. We should make haste.

EditorData.NodeContext: played just debuffed her romantically - she's hiding the fact she's upset

Text.Value: Then the sooner get our vengeance, the better.
It may become more - I hope that it does - but it may also become the cold ash that follows the flame. Or another story written in scars.
I was not suggesting they be allowed to roam free. They should be put to work - the city needs labourers, and fodder to protect it.
I could not enjoy the taste of food for fear of poisoning, and I could not enjoy the company of lovers and friends because I feared they hid knives behind their smiles.
*Alurlssrin. It is a word used rarely, describing the deepest bonds of trust and love.*
I understand you well enough, but I don't like you very much.
I did not expect to find any outside the Underdark who saw the world as I do, and wanted from the world what I want.
While Orin lives, I fear we will not last long at all, whether together or apart. We must find her, and kill her.
The people aren't gullible enough to believe everything they read.
*She joins her thoughts with yours, and you are as one. You share in her strength of mind and formidable will, but also the doubts that eat at her conviction.*
That would be a good life.
Go. We will not speak of this again.
I will be satisfied to have you as an ally.
Yes. I am surprised the house matrons of Menzoberranzan have not discovered the power of the printing press yet.
I would not do that again unless I had reason to think you were hiding something from me. And I do not.
You have your vengeance. How does it feel?
*At first she seems to invite you inside, but then a coldness settles across your mind like morning frost, and you lose contact with her.*
Hmmm. The weak and the elderly perhaps.
Like a dream half-realised. Our fight is not done.
Now you can have me instead.
*What does she see?*
*The cold shell of Minthara's mind melts away, and you are drawn into the heart of her - warm, passionate, and dangerous.*
I am no longer simply its host - I am its mistress.
A friend.
I see the change in the shimmer of your skin, and hear it in the hum of your blood. You are evolving.
I did not expect you.
I hope our bond will last beyond that.
Propaganda is a dangerous weapon.
What are you apologising for?
If you discover any, do share. When I am stronger, we are stronger.

EditorData.NodeContext: End of this branch of conversation. After this line it jumps back to a ton of unrelated questions

Text.Value: You see a future for us once our enemies are dead? I am not so sure.
That is your gift to me, and we are bound together until it is done.
Yes, I have another in my pack. You're welcome to it.
The parasites are rare - I'm not sharing them.
Whatever the case, it will be a short story if Orin has her way. We must find her, and kill her.
Why the sudden interest in my thoughts?
There is little relief to be found from the heat of the storm we are caught in.
While the brain is still free, and we are still infected, we will never be safe.
You wouldn't enjoy seeing what I think of you.
I hope so too.
You're rather special yourself.
Curiosity.
If you trust me, why do you need to poke around inside my head.
When we first met, I did not think we would ever share anything more than an uneasy alliance, born of our mutual enmity for the Absolute.
An ally.
I could not have faced her without you.
You are different - a pleasant surprise. One of the first in my long life.
Our fight isn't over yet. Not until we confront the elder brain.
All I ask is that you do not waste it.
There's nothing I want more.
The young would be better used as a labour force than as a source of nutrition.
I have been told that I am special since my mother first held me in her arms. The burden of expectation.
Bad idea. You wouldn't like what you saw.
We fight side by side. That is enough.
Fine. Perhaps it is for the best that your thoughts stay hidden. I may not know what I am, but I know what I want.
Perhaps it is why they will allow us to rule in his place when the time comes.
Given your hatred of the cult, I thought you might want to avoid the tadpoles.
We are both survivors. But I hoped you saw me as more than that.
The tadpole you harvested is not a curiosity to be pickled and studied - it is a weapon that can unlock the potential of our own parasites.
Is that so? I suppose that is why they have allowed a tyrannical servant of Bane to take control of their city.
As you wish. It is a rare occasion when I do not get what I want - but you have shown your worth in many ways.
We should focus on the fight.
You're welcome to take it.
We need to trust one another if we are to survive, but I want more from you than that. I want all of you.
I have never lacked confidence, but this conflict seems so much bigger than the two of us... it frightens me. I do not know if we will survive it.
No. I don't want to leave them.
A lover.
You should be. On those rare occasions when people have surprised me in the past, I received new scars to remember them by.
Is that so? I suppose it explains why they allowed a tyrannical servant of Bane to take control of their city.
I did not expect to meet another outcast from the Underdark who understood me.
Given your hatred of the cult, I thought you might want to avoid the tadpoles.
Only if I can see your thoughts as well.
Tonight there will be no voices, no orders, no gods... I belong only to you.
I am suggesting they be fed and sheltered, and that they work in return. Call it whatever you wish.
Our fight isn't over yet. Not while Gortash still stands.
I do not often doubt myself, but surviving Orin took courage and strength I was not sure I had.
Without Lolth, without the Absolute... without my home. I do not know myself. But you do, I think.
I'm surprised to hear you suggesting aid for those in need.
Then perhaps you are right to keep it from me. I may not know what I am, but I know what I want.
To kill one's enemies with a well-rounded phrase... that is true power.
I was wrong. A deeper bond has grown between us.
If you controlled the Mouth, what would you have it say?
I also knew that my inherited privilege came with a cost - that the bonds of fellowship and family could be broken by envy and ambition.
An excellent question.
If you ever hesitate to indulge your illithid potential, remember that I will not.
In that case, the sooner we kill Orin the better.

Synopsis: Default Dialogue - the conversation you can have with Minthara at any thime when she's a member of your party. You can ask her about herself, or events that you've experienced together during your adventures. Her responses to you may differ based on some of the choices you make after she joins. Provided you don't betray her for another, she will continue to stand by you, revelling in the violence that follows.
